  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - SHADOWKNIGHT</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>SHADOWKNIGHT PVP LVL 15-HIGH 20S</font> - <small>wagon dragon, Rallos Zek</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>First off, the obvious:  Get as much nodrop gear as possible.  Shin stuff is pretty easy to get, and not too shabby for this lvl.  Others have mentioned additional nodrop eqiupment, so I won't get into that.<p>When looking to PvP, you want to wear only nodrop and stuff you dont mind losing, because you will lose some of it.  Some people also stick to only nodrop for leveling, but it's not that hard to escape pk situations for the most part, as long as you watch your hp and where in the zone you are located (ie dont sit on the main highway when you have 50hp left).<p>As for weapons, there are two trains of thought.  One is "faster is better," go for disrupts.  While disrupts are nice, you often won't do enough damage with a light weapon to get a kill.  When you slowly chip away at someone, they will eventually realize that they're not going to win.  At that point they will attempt to escape, and often times a determined attempt to escape at at least half health will suceed.  My thinking on this issue is to deal damage in large chunks, so by the time they realize they're going to die you have already hit the Harm Touch hotkey.<p>A particularly nasty way to kill casters is to eqiup the highest damage weapon you can get your paws on and sneak up behind a caster while they are distracted.  Then hit auto-attack and wait for your weapon to swing.  If it misses, the caster may not even notice (a lot of people filter the combat dialog to reduce spam).  If they don't react, just keep standing there until you land a blow.  When you do land a blow, or if you miss and they notice, immediately hit them with Clinging Darkness.  Why Clinging?  Because it casts a lot faster than Engulfing and takes a lot less mana.  If things do not go perfectly, you may have to Darkness your target a couple times throughout the fight, or you may need to Fear a pet, Shadow Step away, etc.  You want to make sure you have enough mana for that.  Also, considering the resist rate on Darkness, you're in a much better position if one Clinging gets resisted than if an Engulfing won't stick.<p>So now they're hurt and can't move very fast.  Usually you can get at least another round in before they start taking effective action.  If you used that really big weapon and got a couple hits in, they should be near half health.  Just whack a couple more times (bash if they try to Gate, Root, Mesmerize, Snare, Heal, or Darkness, but ignore damage spells) and they should be within a Harm Touch of death.<p>So now you have a dead corpse ready to loot.  Because SKs are a melee class, we don't really have to worry about not being close enough to loot when we kill, but you do have to be on your toes about right clicking the second you see "you have slain suchandsuch."  You should also make sure your inventory doesn't have any empty slots, so any item you loot will go directly into a container.  Unless they got off a few damage spells, you should be doing all right on health, so take a few moments to find something worthwhile to loot.  It's unlikely that anyone will be able to kill you right away (just pay attention) and nothing sucks like getting a kill on someone with good gear, but looting a cloth cape.<p>Why do I assume that you will be fighting a caster?  Because melees simply have too many hp to PK as another melee.  If you try a warrior--for example--they will eventually resist a couple Darknesses in a row and get away, or quite possibly just turn around and hack you to death.  Plus casters do most of the PKing, so you'll be sure to end up in a lot of vs. caster battles.<p>As for pets, use them if you can.  The disrupts could be critical, and the extra damage doesn't hurt.  Just remember to call off your pet at the last minute so it doesn't get the kill.  If your target has a damage shield, the pet will attack again every time you take damage from the shield.  Also, smart players will attack the pet when they realize they're going to die, so the pet agros on them and has a chance for the kill.  Pay attention.  In most situations, pets are probably out of the question, though.  They take a large percentage of your mana and if you zone a lot (most PvPers do) you will find yourself constantly low on mana and bonechips.<p>These strategies won't make you a PvP god, but they are effective.  I have killed a lvl 26 necro (without pet of course) when I was lvl 23, using the above tactics.  The reasons I won were a) I conserved my mana by only using Clinging Darkness and b) I only used bash when he would cast Shadow Step or a LifeTap.  Come to think of it, I should stress that you want to be very careful about when you use bash.  Your bash doesn't recycle nearly as fast as a caster can recast spells, so you have to learn which spells are important to stop, and what the casting animation/text message are.</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
